Recorded at 3:06 pm (half hour before low tide) from Steep Hill Beach with recorder protected from wind by two large rocks (holding the recorder a few inches off the ground).

NOTES: Large flocks of scoters were active in the channel. Birds were diving and feeding along the rock jetty. Many males were calling. Usually in small groups with females present. There appeared to be atleast two call types. The longer, melancholy whistles presumably given by courting males, and short piping whistles (2:35) which may serve as contact calls. The first segment of this recording was made with a telinga mono parabola - the remainder with the 30" roche. Loud wing whistle in this recording belongs to Surf Scoter (compare to LNS 130901). Number of individuals=AM1-5;.
